    <id>http://deshipu.art/projects/project-184163/</id>
    <title>Vegemite Sandwich Keyboard</title>
    <updated>2022-02-24T00:00:00+01:00</updated>
    <content type="html">&lt;section id="vegemite-sandwich-keyboard"&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Will ESP32-S3 work in a keyboard?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="project-thumb"&gt;
&lt;a class="reference external image-reference" href="/_images/1075201645736111353.jpg"&gt;&lt;img alt="projects/project-184163/images/1075201645736111353.jpg" src="projects/project-184163/images/1075201645736111353.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight-none notranslate"&gt;&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;The ESP32-S3 is the first Espressif board that has both true USB and
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bluetooth, so naturally you have to wonder if it’s any good for
keyboards. I decided to try and see.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I’m using &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://hackaday.io/hacker/264362"&gt;&amp;#64;Unexpected Maker&lt;/a&gt; ‘s &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://tinys3.com"&gt;TinyS3&lt;/a&gt;  boards that just arrived from Australia, hence the board’s name. And
the fact it’s shaped a little bit like a sandwich, if you squint a
little.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It’s also my first board where I’m using switch sockets, so you can
rearrange and replace the switches on it as you like.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;section id="logs"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Logs&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul class="postlist-style-none postlist simple"&gt;
&lt;li class="ablog-post"&gt;&lt;p class="ablog-post-title"&gt;2022-03-03 - &lt;a class="reference internal" href="../../../projects/project-184163/log-203681/"&gt;Wired Mode&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;section id="instructions"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Instructions&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
</content>
